have the Ghetto patrolled.

00:35:31.480 --> 00:35:35.170
But, as the court is aware,
freedom of contract is one

00:35:35.170 --> 00:35:36.900
of these great things where,

00:35:36.900 --> 00:35:40.450
whatever the generally applicable
law is, two people can sit down

00:35:40.450 --> 00:35:44.310
and agree-- this is what you
will do, this is what I will do,

00:35:44.310 --> 00:35:46.790
and they make their
own law essentially.

00:35:46.790 --> 00:35:50.950
And, so, my client was
very angry and very upset,

00:35:50.950 --> 00:35:55.790
when in this one aspect of his
life that he could control,

00:35:55.790 --> 00:35:58.510
his rights were not
being recognized.

00:35:58.510 --> 00:36:02.340
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg:
We heard that Shylock was

00:36:02.340 --> 00:36:07.570
in a state of extreme distress.

00:36:07.570 --> 00:36:15.800
Are you making any plea
that he would be incompetent

00:36:15.800 --> 00:36:26.620 position:56%
to have been accused of a criminal
action, because he was so distraught

00:36:26.620 --> 00:36:31.770
at his daughter's elopement, and
her theft of his worldly goods?

00:36:33.110 --> 00:36:34.480
&gt;&gt; Michael Klotz: Your
Honor, we're not arguing

00:36:34.480 --> 00:36:36.110
that Shylock was incompetent.

00:36:36.110 --> 00:36:38.560
We're arguing that, first of all,

00:36:38.560 --> 00:36:41.770
he didn't have an intent
to murder Antonio.

00:36:41.770 --> 00:36:45.900
His intent was to rebel, to
protest against this circumstance

00:36:45.900 --> 00:36:47.660
that he found himself in.

00:36:47.660 --> 00:36:51.200
And on the second point, that even
if the court were somehow to find

00:36:51.200 --> 00:36:54.690
that he had an intent to
murder, there's no act.

00:36:54.690 --> 00:36:59.200
There's no act of actually
doing anything.

00:36:59.200 --> 00:37:02.430
He can't be convicted for
murderous words any more

00:37:02.430 --> 00:37:05.620
than anyone else could
saying, "I want to do this."

00:37:05.620 --> 00:37:09.550
I mean his situation, Your
Honor, would be comparable

00:37:09.550 --> 00:37:14.460
to a murder trial where a parent
comes in, and says to the court,

00:37:14.460 --> 00:37:16.450
"This man should be executed."

00:37:16.450 --> 00:37:18.710
And then that person
was arrested for murder.

00:37:18.710 --> 00:37:21.540
I mean that would be a
relatively similar situation.

00:37:21.540 --> 00:37:23.120
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg: I thought
you started out with the point

00:37:23.120 --> 00:37:26.240 position:56%
that he couldn't be tried for murder

00:37:26.240 --> 00:37:32.770
when all he did was bring a
civil suit to enforce a contract?

00:37:32.770 --> 00:37:36.510
&gt;&gt; Michael Klotz: Yes, Your Honor.

00:37:36.510 --> 00:37:40.690
[ Laughter ]

00:37:40.690 --> 00:37:43.190
No, I think both things are true.

00:37:43.190 --> 00:37:47.360
I think that it's totally
inappropriate, and it makes,

00:37:47.360 --> 00:37:51.210
you know, it's totally
inappropriate that any request

00:37:51.210 --> 00:37:54.280
of a court could be a criminal act.

00:37:54.280 --> 00:37:57.610
And, so, for that reason I
don't think it's possible

00:37:57.610 --> 00:37:59.670
to convict him under the Alien Act.

00:37:59.670 --> 00:38:02.640
I don't think there's any way
that this can be attempted murder.

00:38:02.640 --> 00:38:06.440
And, separately, in a
not inconsistent point,

00:38:06.440 --> 00:38:07.780
he didn't do anything.

00:38:07.780 --> 00:38:12.460
I mean during this scene he
had a knife, and he, you know,

00:38:12.460 --> 00:38:15.260
he said some words
that he may regret.

00:38:16.400 --> 00:38:18.790
[ Laughter ]

00:38:18.790 --> 00:38:22.360
But nothing else happened.

00:38:22.360 --> 00:38:23.660
&gt;&gt; Richard Schneider:
But the question

00:38:23.660 --> 00:38:25.730
of motive is important to us.

00:38:25.730 --> 00:38:29.560
It's important in terms of
thinking of what Shylock did,

00:38:29.560 --> 00:38:31.360
and how we should rule here.

00:38:31.360 --> 00:38:34.770
I mean one motive is revenge.

00:38:34.770 --> 00:38:37.360
You know, which obviously would
be caught up with the murder.

00:38:37.360 --> 00:38:39.280
But you make an argument
in your brief,

00:38:39.280 --> 00:38:44.120 position:56%
and that you just mentioned a
minute ago, that Shylock was in fact

00:38:44.120 --> 00:38:48.430
in a sense rebelling
through this contract.

00:38:48.430 --> 00:38:50.600
I'm not sure I really
understand what you mean by that.

00:38:50.600 --> 00:38:53.100
Maybe could you elaborate a
little bit on that for us?

00:38:53.100 --> 00:38:54.990
What do you mean?

00:38:54.990 --> 00:38:59.350
What was Shylock doing
here if it wasn't revenge?

00:38:59.350 --> 00:39:00.650
&gt;&gt; Michael Klotz: Yes, Your Honor.

00:39:00.650 --> 00:39:04.740 position:56%
So I mean the attempt to enforce the
penalty provision was a rebellion

00:39:04.740 --> 00:39:09.670
against the Venetian laws that
treated him so differently.

00:39:09.670 --> 00:39:14.450
And then this is the one area
where he was able to do something.

00:39:14.450 --> 00:39:18.000
You know, he was able to sort
of set the terms of his life.

00:39:18.000 --> 00:39:21.670
And the other part of it is during
the proceeding what Shylock points

00:39:21.670 --> 00:39:25.170
out about Antonio and the
other Venetian merchants is the

00:39:25.170 --> 00:39:27.230
incredible hypocrisy.

00:39:27.230 --> 00:39:32.010
You know, Venetian capitalism, you
know, there's trade in many things,

00:39:32.010 --> 00:39:36.040
but one of the main aspects
of trade was slavery.

00:39:36.040 --> 00:39:43.320
And, so, it seems very hypocritical
and improper that merchants

00:39:43.320 --> 00:39:44.830
like Antonio should be able

00:39:44.830 --> 00:39:48.670
to grow wealthy selling
people against their will.

00:39:48.670 --> 00:39:50.630
And my client should not be able

00:39:50.630 --> 00:39:56.310
to recover the penalty provision
even though there's a, you know,

00:39:56.310 --> 00:39:58.510
there's a physical component to it.

00:39:58.510 --> 00:40:04.230
[ Inaudible Speakers ]

00:40:04.230 --> 00:40:05.650
&gt;&gt; Connie Morella: You know,
I'm trying to understand

00:40:05.650 --> 00:40:07.440
that there was a contract.

00:40:07.440 --> 00:40:13.490
They actually made a legal contract
even though Shylock said something

00:40:13.490 --> 00:40:15.910
about it being a merry
joke or something,

00:40:15.910 --> 00:40:21.000 position:56%
which meant that they fully expected
the money would be returned on time.

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:25.880
But then he perseveres
for the pound of flesh.

00:40:25.880 --> 00:40:29.330
But then when he finds out
about the blood, you know,

00:40:29.330 --> 00:40:31.750
and he says he wants it by a heart.

00:40:31.750 --> 00:40:34.670
Did he think it could be
done in some other way

00:40:34.670 --> 00:40:38.980
so that Antonio would not die?

00:40:38.980 --> 00:40:44.670
I mean what did you find
out in your investigation

00:40:44.670 --> 00:40:50.040
of this case what he had in mind?

00:40:50.040 --> 00:40:52.060
&gt;&gt; Michael Klotz: Shylock
didn't intend to murder,

00:40:52.060 --> 00:40:54.280
and did not intend
to murder Antonio.

00:40:54.280 --> 00:40:55.580
It was a pound of flesh.

00:40:55.580 --> 00:41:01.410
It was not a dagger in the
heart or anything like that.

00:41:01.410 --> 00:41:03.660
&gt;&gt; Connie Morella: He
wanted it near the heart.

00:41:03.660 --> 00:41:04.960
And, yeah--

00:41:04.960 --> 00:41:08.130
&gt;&gt; Michael Klotz: He
wanted it near the heart.

00:41:08.130 --> 00:41:13.220 position:56%
But the court doesn't know any more
than I do if he'd been granted that,

00:41:13.220 --> 00:41:16.250
if Portia had granted him
that right, and she'd enforce

00:41:16.250 --> 00:41:18.740
that right of specific performance.

00:41:18.740 --> 00:41:21.780
He might have dropped the knife,
and asked for the money instead.

00:41:21.780 --> 00:41:25.180
I mean there's no way
to know at this point.

00:41:25.180 --> 00:41:26.480
&gt;&gt; Connie Morella: Mr. Klotz,--

00:41:26.480 --> 00:41:28.700
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg: In any
case the money we have settled,

00:41:28.700 --> 00:41:31.220
the pound of flesh is
out of the case now.

00:41:31.220 --> 00:41:34.810
It's just a matter of money.

00:41:34.810 --> 00:41:36.110
&gt;&gt; Michael Klotz: Yes, Your Honor.

00:41:36.110 --> 00:41:37.410
No, we're not seeking
the pound of flesh.

00:41:37.410 --> 00:41:41.470
And after all this time we're not
trying to cut, we're not trying

00:41:41.470 --> 00:41:43.470
to come and have that be enforced.

00:41:43.470 --> 00:41:45.360
&gt;&gt; Suzanne Reynolds: But if
you're seeking, Mr. Klotz,

00:41:45.360 --> 00:41:48.160
if you're just focusing
on the civil action,

00:41:48.160 --> 00:41:51.030
and you're not seeking
the pound of flesh,

00:41:51.030 --> 00:41:57.230
you're seeking only the repayment
of the money plus interest,

00:41:57.230 --> 00:42:01.020 position:56%
isn't this a claim not raised below?

00:42:01.020 --> 00:42:02.500
This is an appellate court.

00:42:02.500 --> 00:42:07.290
Did you raise this claim below?

00:42:07.290 --> 00:42:09.570
[ Laughter ]

00:42:09.570 --> 00:42:12.510
&gt;&gt; Michael Klotz: That's a
great question, Your Honor.

00:42:12.510 --> 00:42:16.560
[ Laughter ]

00:42:16.560 --> 00:42:18.510
&gt;&gt; Suzanne Reynolds: Thank you.

00:42:18.510 --> 00:42:22.640
[ Laughter ]

00:42:22.640 --> 00:42:25.430
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg: I take it
you're seeking a substitutional

00:42:25.430 --> 00:42:30.690
remedy since the one you asked
for the law did not permit.

00:42:30.690 --> 00:42:33.050
&gt;&gt; Michael Klotz: Well,
what I think, Your Honor,

00:42:33.050 --> 00:42:37.540
is I mean the proceeding
obviously was totally improper

00:42:37.540 --> 00:42:39.660
with Portia acting as the judge.

00:42:39.660 --> 00:42:42.290
But the other main point that
we haven't discussed yet,

00:42:42.290 --> 00:42:45.600
but is discussed in the brief,
is the incredible duress

00:42:45.600 --> 00:42:48.370 position:56%
for my client during the proceeding.

00:42:48.370 --> 00:42:51.440
First Portia says, you know,
"You can get the pound of flesh.

00:42:51.440 --> 00:42:52.740
You don't get blood.

00:42:52.740 --> 00:42:55.280
You don't get any more
or less than that."

00:42:55.280 --> 00:42:59.610
Shylock then asked for the
money, and was told no.

00:42:59.610 --> 00:43:04.170
Portia then said that he
violated the Alien Act supposedly

00:43:04.170 --> 00:43:06.450
for making this request
of the court.

00:43:06.450 --> 00:43:11.730
And then Shylock was forced
to convert to Christianity.

00:43:11.730 --> 00:43:14.210
And the Duke said very
clearly if he didn't do

00:43:14.210 --> 00:43:17.130
that then he was going
to be executed.

00:43:17.130 --> 00:43:20.140
So to the extent that
there's a waiver argument,

00:43:20.140 --> 00:43:23.010
I think that maybe we
can let that slide.

00:43:23.010 --> 00:43:25.000
[ Laughter ]

00:43:34.270 --> 00:43:36.920
But we're asking this
court in addition,

00:43:36.920 --> 00:43:39.540
to follow up on your point,
besides the civil remedy,

00:43:39.540 --> 00:43:43.290
which is the return of the
3,000 ducats and the interest,

00:43:43.290 --> 00:43:48.840
we're asking to have my client's
name cleared after all this time.

00:43:48.840 --> 00:43:51.020
There's nothing that, you know,
there's nothing that we can do

00:43:51.020 --> 00:43:53.980
about this improper
verdict other than to,

00:43:53.980 --> 00:43:56.370
you know, completely nullify it.

00:43:56.370 --> 00:43:59.290
&gt;&gt; Richard Schneider: You made
a comment about the Alien Act.

00:43:59.290 --> 00:44:02.470
Are you arguing that
the Alien Act in itself,

00:44:02.470 --> 00:44:05.830
and maybe you could explain exactly
what that is, but the Alien Act,

00:44:05.830 --> 00:44:09.480
are you arguing that that
is somehow illegitimate,

00:44:09.480 --> 00:44:14.530
or are you just simply saying it
was wrongly applied to Shylock?

00:44:15.690 --> 00:44:19.510
&gt;&gt; Michael Klotz: The Alien
Act is totally illegitimate.

00:44:19.510 --> 00:44:23.170
I mean it's an act that has
completely disparate treatment

00:44:23.170 --> 00:44:24.940
of a certain group of people.

00:44:24.940 --> 00:44:27.180
It protects Venetian
citizens in a way

00:44:27.180 --> 00:44:30.900
that non-citizens would
not be protected.

00:44:30.900 --> 00:44:34.480
If somebody were to have made
an attempt to murder my client,

00:44:34.480 --> 00:44:37.610
Shylock, that wouldn't
have been a violation.

00:44:37.610 --> 00:44:40.650
And nothing would have
happened whatsoever.

00:44:40.650 --> 00:44:44.710
And just to give an example from
our case, you know, the Duke saying

00:44:44.710 --> 00:44:48.500
to Shylock, "If you don't
convert to Christianity I'm going

00:44:48.500 --> 00:44:52.230
to execute you," you know,
that seems very similar.

00:44:52.230 --> 00:44:58.140
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg: But didn't
you consider that the only chance

00:44:58.140 --> 00:45:04.280
that Shylock had for salvation,
so far from being a penalty,

00:45:04.280 --> 00:45:10.850
it was a tremendous advantage
to Shylock to be converted

00:45:10.850 --> 00:45:15.510
to a Christian, so then
his soul could be saved.

00:45:15.510 --> 00:45:20.080
[ Laughter ]

00:45:20.080 --> 00:45:21.810
&gt;&gt; Michael Klotz: You're
absolutely correct, Your Honor.

00:45:21.810 --> 00:45:26.360
I think that's what he believed.

00:45:26.360 --> 00:45:29.490
&gt;&gt; Richard Schneider: But, in other
words, the Duke was acting very,

00:45:29.490 --> 00:45:32.290
the Duke was acting mercifully.

00:45:32.290 --> 00:45:38.750
And Shylock, who Portia begged
to act mercifully, never did.

00:45:38.750 --> 00:45:44.140
Shylock refused up
until the last minute

00:45:44.140 --> 00:45:48.000
to renounce the pound of flesh.

00:45:53.040 --> 00:45:56.480
&gt;&gt; Michael Klotz: We can't dispute,
Your Honor, that Shylock didn't act

00:45:56.480 --> 00:46:00.020
with all the mercy that he
could have in this proceeding.

00:46:00.020 --> 00:46:05.250
But I believe that the factors
that we've talked about, you know,

00:46:05.250 --> 00:46:08.490
the treatment that he experienced.

00:46:08.490 --> 00:46:11.300
His view that if he
doesn't have his rights

00:46:11.300 --> 00:46:14.000
under the contract what
rights does he have?

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:18.530
He's already treated in this
totally unfair and disparate way.

00:46:18.530 --> 00:46:24.810
And, you know, the
audacity of Antonio to act

00:46:24.810 --> 00:46:27.610
as though this penalty
provision that he'd agreed upon,

00:46:27.610 --> 00:46:31.250
and they talked about in detail,
and they'd negotiated, and they'd,

00:46:31.250 --> 00:46:34.790
you know, reduced to writing,
was somehow an outrage.

00:46:34.790 --> 00:46:39.260
And Shylock was, you know,
beyond the pale in trying

00:46:39.260 --> 00:46:42.660
to enforce the terms
that they had agreed on.

00:46:42.660 --> 00:46:48.680
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg: Do you say
he did not violate the alien rule

00:46:48.680 --> 00:46:54.140
because he didn't actually
perform anything against Antonio,

00:46:54.140 --> 00:46:56.600
even though he may have wanted to?

00:46:56.600 --> 00:46:59.070
&gt;&gt; Michael Klotz: That's
exactly right, Your Honor.

00:47:00.390 --> 00:47:01.690
&gt;&gt; Richard Schneider: Okay.

00:47:01.690 --> 00:47:06.950
Your time is almost up, so do you
want to just quickly sum up and--

00:47:06.950 --> 00:47:08.250
&gt;&gt; Michael Klotz: Yes, Your Honor.

00:47:08.250 --> 00:47:10.670
To reiterate, we asked
the court to once

00:47:10.670 --> 00:47:15.050
and for all vacate the decision
below without leave for a retrial

00:47:15.050 --> 00:47:20.580
of my client, that the 3,000
ducats be returned in full,

00:47:20.580 --> 00:47:25.880
that he be awarded interest on
that money after all this time,

00:47:25.880 --> 00:47:29.250
and that the court
awards such further relief

00:47:29.250 --> 00:47:33.160
as you think is appropriate,
particularly in light of what he

00:47:33.160 --> 00:47:37.370
and other Jewish residents
in Venice suffered.

00:47:37.370 --> 00:47:39.080
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg:
Thank you, Counsel.

00:47:39.080 --> 00:47:41.510
&gt;&gt; Michael Klotz: Thank you.

00:47:41.510 --> 00:47:49.040
[ Applause ]

00:47:49.040 --> 00:47:51.950
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg: We will now
hear for Counsel for the Merchant

00:47:51.950 --> 00:47:55.640
of Venice, Antonio, and
the Republic of Venice.

00:47:55.640 --> 00:47:56.940
&gt;&gt; Eugene Gulland:
Thank you, Your Honor.

00:47:56.940 --> 00:48:00.010
And may it please the
court, I want to begin

00:48:00.010 --> 00:48:03.970
by rejecting the transparently
false narrative

00:48:03.970 --> 00:48:06.140 position:56%
that we've been presented with here.

00:48:06.140 --> 00:48:13.490
The notion that Shylock was
engaged simply in a noble

00:48:13.490 --> 00:48:18.160
and honorable protest of what he
thought to be the deficiencies

00:48:18.160 --> 00:48:23.870
and unfairness of Venetian
law, that is simply not true.

00:48:23.870 --> 00:48:27.290
Never until this appeal
have we heard that argument.

00:48:27.290 --> 00:48:31.700
And indeed if we look at the
record of the case, again and again

00:48:31.700 --> 00:48:38.720
and again it shows that Shylock
entered into a premeditated

00:48:38.720 --> 00:48:44.040
and deceitful course of action
in order to lure Antonio

00:48:44.040 --> 00:48:49.640
into sealing a bond that would be
the means of his own destruction.

00:48:49.640 --> 00:48:52.920
And there are four critical
elements in this scheme.

00:48:52.920 --> 00:48:56.090
They're undisputed in
the record of the case.

00:48:56.090 --> 00:49:01.230
First, throughout Shylock
admitted to his motives.

00:49:01.230 --> 00:49:05.560
Even before he negotiated the
penalty bond, he was overheard

00:49:05.560 --> 00:49:11.970
to say quote, speaking of Antonio,
I hate him for he is a Christian.

00:49:11.970 --> 00:49:14.890
If I can catch him once on the hip,

00:49:14.890 --> 00:49:19.670
I will feed fat the
ancient grudge I bear him.

00:49:19.670 --> 00:49:26.580
In fact we heard Shylock himself a
few minutes ago say that the pound

00:49:26.580 --> 00:49:30.590
of flesh would be used
to bait fish withal.

00:49:30.590 --> 00:49:37.210
And that further he would use that
pound of flesh to feed his revenge.

00:49:37.210 --> 00:49:41.970
Other evidence of the
motive of revenge

00:49:41.970 --> 00:49:45.620
and hatred abounds throughout
the record of this case.

00:49:45.620 --> 00:49:49.510
But if there were any doubt
it would have been satisfied

00:49:49.510 --> 00:49:54.400
when at his trial, in response
to questions by the Duke,

00:49:54.400 --> 00:49:58.020
he explained that his motive
was a, quote, lodged hate

00:49:58.020 --> 00:50:02.040
and a certain loathing,
end quote, for Antonio.

00:50:02.040 --> 00:50:05.160
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg: Counsel,
before we get into your discussion

00:50:05.160 --> 00:50:09.620
of the merits of a criminal
prosecution, I think you conceded

00:50:09.620 --> 00:50:16.830
at the outset that that turn of
the proceedings from a civil suit

00:50:16.830 --> 00:50:18.600
to enforce a contract

00:50:18.600 --> 00:50:25.160
into a criminal case was
highly inappropriate.

00:50:25.160 --> 00:50:27.630
Did you not make that
concession in your brief?

00:50:27.630 --> 00:50:29.240
&gt;&gt; Eugene Gulland: Well, I
think we have two responses

00:50:29.240 --> 00:50:30.540
to that, Your Honor.

00:50:30.540 --> 00:50:36.260
The first is that Antonio
was permitted to use

00:50:36.260 --> 00:50:40.080
as a counterclaim [inaudible]
a defense any law

00:50:40.080 --> 00:50:41.380
that would be available--

00:50:41.380 --> 00:50:42.680
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg:
Can you bring--

00:50:42.680 --> 00:50:43.980
&gt;&gt; Eugene Gulland: To him.

00:50:43.980 --> 00:50:45.280
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg:

00:50:45.280 --> 00:50:46.580
Can you bring in a civil
case a criminal prosecution

00:50:46.580 --> 00:50:47.880
as a counterclaim?

00:50:47.880 --> 00:50:49.240 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Eugene Gulland: Yeah, absolutely.

00:50:49.240 --> 00:50:51.010
Under the--

00:50:51.010 --> 00:50:52.400
[ Laughter ]

00:50:52.400 --> 00:50:54.990
Under the law of Venice
at that time this kind

00:50:54.990 --> 00:50:57.010
of pleading was recognized.

00:50:57.010 --> 00:51:01.120 position:56%
But, as we argued in our brief, Your
Honor, we have an additional point.

00:51:01.120 --> 00:51:05.940
And that is we do agree
on one point with Shylock.

00:51:05.940 --> 00:51:10.060
And that is that the
procedures were flawed by reason

00:51:10.060 --> 00:51:13.480
of Portia's misrepresentations
in masquerade.

00:51:13.480 --> 00:51:19.720 position:56%
And for that reason we've asked this
court to consider the case de novo.

00:51:19.720 --> 00:51:21.020
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg: Well,

00:51:21.020 --> 00:51:26.870
we have as Judge [inaudible]
reminded us, that this is a court

00:51:26.870 --> 00:51:30.700
of review, not of first view.

00:51:30.700 --> 00:51:37.170
De novo, we would be looking at the
case as a court of first instance.

00:51:37.170 --> 00:51:41.380
But we are an appellate forum.

00:51:41.380 --> 00:51:45.530
So we have no authority
to hear witnesses.

00:51:45.530 --> 00:51:49.800
We judge the case according
to the law.

00:51:49.800 --> 00:51:55.580
So I don't understand how you
could ask this court to serve

00:51:55.580 --> 00:51:59.810
as a first instance, de novo court.

00:51:59.810 --> 00:52:02.620
&gt;&gt; Eugene Gulland: Well, even
if this court should decline

00:52:02.620 --> 00:52:08.190
to consider the case
entirely anew, the opportunity

00:52:08.190 --> 00:52:11.980
through representation by very
able counsel, and the opportunity

00:52:11.980 --> 00:52:17.520 position:56%
to make all of his arguments ensures
that Shylock now has the right

00:52:17.520 --> 00:52:22.310
to argue against the application
of the alien law to him.

00:52:22.310 --> 00:52:28.560
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg: And
with the proceeding is improper,

00:52:28.560 --> 00:52:34.730
then I suppose an appellate
court should just dismiss it.

00:52:35.760 --> 00:52:40.760
And if it dismisses the
case and then where are we?

00:52:40.760 --> 00:52:45.110
&gt;&gt; Eugene Gulland: Well, if this
court simply dismissed the case,

00:52:45.110 --> 00:52:48.230
then I think it would put
Antonio and the Duke of Venice

00:52:48.230 --> 00:52:53.590 position:56%
in the position that they would want
to be in, because it would deny any

00:52:53.590 --> 00:52:55.720
and all relief to Shylock.

00:52:55.720 --> 00:52:59.370
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg: But you
are not urging us to do that,

00:52:59.370 --> 00:53:02.470
because you recognize that
he did not get a fair trial.

00:53:02.470 --> 00:53:03.770
Is that it?

00:53:03.770 --> 00:53:05.080
&gt;&gt; Eugene Gulland: We regret

00:53:05.080 --> 00:53:07.710
that the procedures were
not fair procedures.

00:53:07.710 --> 00:53:09.010
Yes.

00:53:09.010 --> 00:53:10.310
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg:
Let me go to what seems

00:53:10.310 --> 00:53:15.070
to be your principle
argument that this was an act

00:53:15.070 --> 00:53:20.500
of vengeance on Shylock's part.

00:53:20.500 --> 00:53:24.460
But Shylock, when the
transaction took place,

00:53:24.460 --> 00:53:30.630
called it a merry sport,
a merry bond.

00:53:30.630 --> 00:53:37.790 position:56%
And a really puzzling aspect of your
position that it's all vengeance,

00:53:37.790 --> 00:53:44.510
at the time this bargain was made
Shylock had every reason to think

00:53:44.510 --> 00:53:47.700
that Antonio, rich
merchant Defendant,

00:53:47.700 --> 00:53:50.130
would be able to repay him.

00:53:50.130 --> 00:53:55.840
He had no idea of the
supposed tragedy at sea.

00:53:55.840 --> 00:54:01.070
He expected, as Antonio
did, that Antonio would be,

00:54:01.070 --> 00:54:06.860
his wealth would be increased
well within the time of the loan.

00:54:06.860 --> 00:54:09.970
&gt;&gt; Eugene Gulland: I
think the record shows

00:54:09.970 --> 00:54:16.180 position:56%
that from the very beginning Shylock
was scheming to trap Antonio.

00:54:16.180 --> 00:54:17.670
He deceived Antonio.

00:54:17.670 --> 00:54:22.720
He said to Antonio, at the time
that they were discussing the bond,

00:54:22.720 --> 00:54:30.750
that he was offering the loan for
reconciliation and friendship.

00:54:30.750 --> 00:54:34.800
He said, quote, I would
be friends with you

00:54:34.800 --> 00:54:37.820
and have your love, to Antonio.

00:54:37.820 --> 00:54:40.990
As you point out, he
jovially referred

00:54:40.990 --> 00:54:44.000
to the penalty bond
as a merry sport.

00:54:44.000 --> 00:54:48.740
And he quickly added
that it was worthless.

00:54:48.740 --> 00:54:52.330
Nobody could expect him to ever
claim the bond, because a pound

00:54:52.330 --> 00:54:58.270 position:56%
of a man's flesh taken from a man
is not estimable, profitable neither

00:54:58.270 --> 00:55:02.360
as flesh from muttons,
beefs and goats.

00:55:02.360 --> 00:55:07.950
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg: But
what basis did Shylock have

00:55:07.950 --> 00:55:13.820
to even suspect that this
question would arise,

00:55:13.820 --> 00:55:18.400
to suspect that Antonio would
not be able to repay him?

00:55:18.400 --> 00:55:21.340
Antonio is a rich merchant.

00:55:21.340 --> 00:55:26.390
There was no premonition
of storms at sea.

00:55:26.390 --> 00:55:33.080
Why would you attribute to
Shylock such a motive of vengeance

00:55:33.080 --> 00:55:36.570
when Shylock had every
reason in the world to expect

00:55:36.570 --> 00:55:40.720
that within the three-months'
time he would be repaid?

00:55:40.720 --> 00:55:43.070
&gt;&gt; Eugene Gulland:
He was laying a trap.

00:55:43.070 --> 00:55:46.920
He understood that he
would probably be repaid.

00:55:46.920 --> 00:55:49.810
But he also understood
that if he were not,

00:55:49.810 --> 00:55:54.350
this would be his opportunity
finally to have the revenge

00:55:54.350 --> 00:55:55.780
that he sought so dearly.

00:55:55.780 --> 00:56:00.090
And there's a little noticed fact

00:56:00.090 --> 00:56:03.060
that is very interesting
in this case.

00:56:03.060 --> 00:56:07.270
And that is when he first
heard about the opportunity

00:56:07.270 --> 00:56:14.070
to have a penalty bond from
Antonio, he didn't have the money.

00:56:14.070 --> 00:56:15.870
Shylock didn't have the money.

00:56:15.870 --> 00:56:17.470
And, so, what did he do?

00:56:17.470 --> 00:56:24.210
He went to his moneylender friend,
Tubal, and borrowed the money

00:56:24.210 --> 00:56:27.660
to lend in order to
get the penalty bond.

00:56:27.660 --> 00:56:32.500
In other words, he was willing
to pay interest to Tubal,

00:56:32.500 --> 00:56:35.810
and make a loan free of charge.

00:56:35.810 --> 00:56:37.110
Free of charge.

00:56:37.110 --> 00:56:41.700
And that was to set up the trap.

00:56:41.700 --> 00:56:46.490
And it shows that throughout, from
the very beginning to the very end,

00:56:46.490 --> 00:56:49.030
that even though he recognized

00:56:49.030 --> 00:56:52.010
that he would probably be
repaid, the trap could be set.

00:56:52.010 --> 00:56:56.820
And he would have his
revenge if he was not repaid.

00:56:56.820 --> 00:56:58.120
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg:
One other thing

00:56:58.120 --> 00:57:01.810
that Shylock was very clear
about, he said it a few times,

00:57:01.810 --> 00:57:04.360
he said, "I crave the law."

00:57:04.360 --> 00:57:07.760
But no one told him
what the law was.

00:57:07.760 --> 00:57:10.530 position:56%
Nobody told him about the Alien Act.

00:57:10.530 --> 00:57:16.990
So it's an obvious case of
no notice or opportunity

00:57:16.990 --> 00:57:20.480
to rethink the case
in light of the law.

00:57:20.480 --> 00:57:22.980
But Shylock craved the law.

00:57:22.980 --> 00:57:28.470 position:56%
Once he's told what the law is, then
the pound of flesh is off the table.

00:57:28.470 --> 00:57:30.820
&gt;&gt; Eugene Gulland: The pound

00:57:30.820 --> 00:57:37.550
of flesh is not a valid
penalty bond under Venetian law.

00:57:37.550 --> 00:57:44.210
Venetian law, it's true,
enforced commercial terms.

00:57:44.210 --> 00:57:48.200
The penalty bond here is
not a commercial term.

00:57:48.200 --> 00:57:51.300
In fact Shylock himself
admitted many times

00:57:51.300 --> 00:57:54.420
that it was not a commercial
term when he said

00:57:54.420 --> 00:58:02.600
that he would gladly give up
repayment of 20 times the loan

00:58:02.600 --> 00:58:05.550
in order to enforce
the penalty bond.

00:58:05.550 --> 00:58:08.130
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg:
But what about the state

00:58:08.130 --> 00:58:12.090
of mind of your client, Antonio?

00:58:12.090 --> 00:58:15.460 position:56%
Why did he agree to this so swiftly?

00:58:15.460 --> 00:58:16.940
&gt;&gt; Richard Schneider: And
just to follow up on that,

00:58:16.940 --> 00:58:18.270
I have a problem with that as well.

00:58:18.270 --> 00:58:20.590
I mean it's not hard for me

00:58:20.590 --> 00:58:23.980
to understand why Shylock
would want this bond,

00:58:23.980 --> 00:58:27.470
whether we think it was revenge or
whether we think it was, you know,

00:58:27.470 --> 00:58:30.400
political expression of some sort.

00:58:30.400 --> 00:58:34.480
But why would Antonio agree
to be bound by this bond?

00:58:34.480 --> 00:58:39.160
Why would he agree to give up
a pound of his own flesh just

00:58:39.160 --> 00:58:41.710
to get money for Bassanio?

00:58:41.710 --> 00:58:44.880
And what I'm thinking here
is really is it possible

00:58:44.880 --> 00:58:48.970
that Antonio was the one
laying the trap for Shylock,

00:58:48.970 --> 00:58:54.720
because Antonio knew that Shylock
would be hit with the Alien Act?

00:58:54.720 --> 00:58:56.400
&gt;&gt; Eugene Gulland: Well,
there's no evidence

00:58:56.400 --> 00:58:57.860
in the record to suggest
[inaudible]--

00:58:57.860 --> 00:58:59.160
&gt;&gt; Richard Schneider:
Well, there may not be--

00:58:59.160 --> 00:59:01.070
[ Laughter ]

00:59:01.070 --> 00:59:03.000
There may not be reference
to the record to that.

00:59:03.000 --> 00:59:04.780
But I'm just speculating.

00:59:04.780 --> 00:59:06.080
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg: Well, may--

00:59:06.080 --> 00:59:07.380
&gt;&gt; Eugene Gulland: The fact--

00:59:07.380 --> 00:59:08.680
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg:
May I interject

00:59:08.680 --> 00:59:13.780
that there are multiple
clues in the record.

00:59:13.780 --> 00:59:19.890
When we first meet
Antonio he said, "In sooth,

00:59:19.890 --> 00:59:23.820
I know not why I am so sad."

00:59:23.820 --> 00:59:30.010
He later says, "I am tainted wether
of the flock, meetest for death."

00:59:30.010 --> 00:59:32.560
Meetest for death.

00:59:32.560 --> 00:59:38.510
So this is a very sad man
who is longing for death.

00:59:38.510 --> 00:59:45.140
[ Laughter ]

00:59:45.140 --> 00:59:48.510
&gt;&gt; Eugene Gulland: I think he
snapped out of that depression.

00:59:48.510 --> 00:59:52.280
[ Laughter ]

00:59:52.280 --> 00:59:56.330
To answer the question,
Antonio was fooled.

00:59:56.330 --> 01:00:01.050
He was taken in by the
reconciliation and friendship

01:00:01.050 --> 01:00:03.880
that he thought were
being offered by Shylock.

01:00:03.880 --> 01:00:10.010
And in fact Antonio, just as he was
going and sealing the bond, said,

01:00:10.010 --> 01:00:16.350
quote, there is much kindness
in the Jew, end quote.

01:00:16.350 --> 01:00:19.660
And I have to say,
although he's my client,

01:00:19.660 --> 01:00:25.310
that Antonio was easy
prey in another sense.

01:00:25.310 --> 01:00:32.930
He was a profoundly, extravagantly
proud man with an extravagant

01:00:32.930 --> 01:00:35.510
and exaggerated sense of honor.

01:00:35.510 --> 01:00:39.640
And Shylock, cunning as he was,

01:00:39.640 --> 01:00:43.440
preyed on this character
defect of Antonio.

01:00:43.440 --> 01:00:45.950
And he did so in the following way.

01:00:45.950 --> 01:00:51.150
He recognized that if it ever came
time to enforce the penalty bond,

01:00:51.150 --> 01:00:56.190
that Antonio would be too
proud to dishonor it, that,

01:00:56.190 --> 01:00:58.350
in other words, he would admit it.

01:00:58.350 --> 01:00:59.730
And that's exactly what happened.

01:00:59.730 --> 01:01:02.420
Antonio didn't hire a lawyer.

01:01:02.420 --> 01:01:05.090
Antonio offered no defense.

01:01:05.090 --> 01:01:10.430
Antonio confessed the bond, and
offered himself up to be killed.

01:01:10.430 --> 01:01:13.540
And that's exactly what
Shylock's scheme was.

01:01:13.540 --> 01:01:15.950
He knew that Antonio
would not resist,

01:01:15.950 --> 01:01:20.250
and that there would be no
genuine court proceeding standing

01:01:20.250 --> 01:01:26.150
between himself and his
opportunity to kill Antonio.

01:01:26.150 --> 01:01:29.990
And that's why the argument
that there was an intercession

01:01:29.990 --> 01:01:35.850
of a court proceeding as a defense
doesn't work, because Shylock,

01:01:35.850 --> 01:01:39.500
taking advantage of
this character flaw,

01:01:39.500 --> 01:01:43.330
knew that there would be no
meaningful judicial protection

01:01:43.330 --> 01:01:44.630
of Antonio.

01:01:44.630 --> 01:01:46.010
&gt;&gt; Connie Morella: Speaking
of being taken advantage of,

01:01:46.010 --> 01:01:51.030 position:56%
don't you think Shylock was in a way
in that he never got due process?

01:01:51.030 --> 01:01:57.960
He never had anybody to advise him
of what the consequences would be,

01:01:57.960 --> 01:02:01.820
or what the journey through
the law would mean for him.

01:02:01.820 --> 01:02:05.610
Is it not amazing to you that
you take a civil case and it ends

01:02:05.610 --> 01:02:07.740
up being a criminal case?

01:02:07.740 --> 01:02:12.330
And, so, should he not have been
given due process along the way?

01:02:12.330 --> 01:02:16.340
&gt;&gt; Eugene Gulland: Well,
let's take it in steps.

01:02:16.340 --> 01:02:21.110
In the negotiation
of the penalty bond,

01:02:21.110 --> 01:02:27.200
I think that Shylock is a
very experienced moneylender,

01:02:27.200 --> 01:02:35.170
was very knowledgeable
about the applicable law.

01:02:35.170 --> 01:02:44.020
And it shows that regardless
of the criticisms,

01:02:44.020 --> 01:02:49.310
we have the Venetian law, court
proceedings were open to Jews

01:02:49.310 --> 01:02:53.780
in Venice, and the protection of
the laws were applicable to them.

01:02:53.780 --> 01:03:01.880
You are right that when his
case got to court, the charade,

01:03:01.880 --> 01:03:06.270
Portia's masquerade, did
deny him due process.

01:03:06.270 --> 01:03:08.860
And we entirely agree with that.

01:03:08.860 --> 01:03:11.410
We think, however, though
on the basis of the record

01:03:11.410 --> 01:03:17.510
and the devastating admissions
repeatedly made by Shylock,

01:03:17.510 --> 01:03:22.670
that he properly stands
convicted of the offense

01:03:22.670 --> 01:03:24.350
of which he was found guilty.

01:03:24.350 --> 01:03:29.470 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg: But how does
the Alien Act come into the picture?

01:03:29.470 --> 01:03:34.590
You just said that Antonio
wasn't putting up any defense.

01:03:34.590 --> 01:03:38.380
He certainly didn't
raise the Alien Act.

01:03:38.380 --> 01:03:44.820
It was this sham lawyer/judge,
Portia, who brought that.

01:03:44.820 --> 01:03:50.480
&gt;&gt; Eugene Gulland: Well, our brief
points out that the intervention

01:03:50.480 --> 01:03:54.780
of Portia indeed saved
the life of Antonio.

01:03:54.780 --> 01:03:57.420
It also saved the life of Shylock.

01:03:57.420 --> 01:04:02.880
And it saved Shylock because
Shylock was ready, willing

01:04:02.880 --> 01:04:06.550
and able to kill Antonio.

01:04:06.550 --> 01:04:12.610
The notion that Antonio
would have been spared

01:04:12.610 --> 01:04:15.790
by Shylock is absolutely crazy.

01:04:15.790 --> 01:04:22.090
The record shows Shylock was
earnestly sharpening his knife

01:04:22.090 --> 01:04:27.840
in the court, that Shylock
had a balance scale in order

01:04:27.840 --> 01:04:31.460
to measure the pound of flesh.

01:04:31.460 --> 01:04:33.680
He was ready to do it.

01:04:33.680 --> 01:04:37.450
And it was only Portia
that saved Antonio,

01:04:37.450 --> 01:04:40.100 position:56%
and also saved Shylock from himself.

01:04:40.100 --> 01:04:43.040
&gt;&gt; Suzanne Reynolds: Counselor,
I'd like to ask a question here.

01:04:43.040 --> 01:04:47.510
I think we'd all agree that the
record is beautifully written.

01:04:47.510 --> 01:04:50.040
[ Laughter ]

01:04:50.040 --> 01:04:54.510
But that it's rather thin, at
least of the court proceeding.

01:04:54.510 --> 01:04:58.260
And I believe that you are
asking us to draw a lot

01:04:58.260 --> 01:05:00.880
of inferences from the record.

01:05:00.880 --> 01:05:05.040
What about this inference
that Shylock never believed

01:05:05.040 --> 01:05:09.890
that the court would allow him
to exact his pound of flesh?

01:05:09.890 --> 01:05:13.370
He does seem surprised
in the court proceeding

01:05:13.370 --> 01:05:15.750
when Portia says, "You're right.

01:05:15.750 --> 01:05:19.100
You may enforce the penalty bond."

01:05:19.100 --> 01:05:23.210
And he praises her, and
sounds very surprised.

01:05:23.210 --> 01:05:28.140 position:56%
Why isn't it, as reasonable
inference as you would have us draw,

01:05:28.140 --> 01:05:32.700
that he was willing to put
the knife to Antonio's heart?

01:05:32.700 --> 01:05:37.530
Why isn't it equally a valid
inference that he never thought

01:05:37.530 --> 01:05:41.890
that the court would allow
him to exact this measure?

01:05:41.890 --> 01:05:46.270 position:56%
Enforced the penalty bond literally?

01:05:46.270 --> 01:05:48.270
&gt;&gt; Eugene Gulland:
Well, with all respect,

01:05:48.270 --> 01:05:51.830
we don't think there's
any question of inference,

01:05:51.830 --> 01:05:54.420
because we have the man's words.

01:05:54.420 --> 01:05:59.240
Again and again and
again, those words, events,

01:05:59.240 --> 01:06:06.440
nothing other than an intent to
execute Antonio, to have revenge,

01:06:06.440 --> 01:06:11.210
and to realize the
longstanding object of his hatred,

01:06:11.210 --> 01:06:13.800
that is the killing of Antonio.

01:06:13.800 --> 01:06:15.520
&gt;&gt; Suzanne Reynolds: But
that's another inference.

01:06:15.520 --> 01:06:18.970
I mean as Justice Ginsburg
pointed out, he did say,

01:06:18.970 --> 01:06:23.020
Shylock said on several
occasions, "This is a merry bond.

01:06:23.020 --> 01:06:26.390
This is nothing to
be worried about."

01:06:26.390 --> 01:06:32.100
And he does appear surprised
when Portia says, "You're right.

01:06:32.100 --> 01:06:38.950
You win." Why is it not a
proper inference for us to draw

01:06:38.950 --> 01:06:42.210
that he might have, since you
want us to draw some inferences

01:06:42.210 --> 01:06:45.290
from the record, why
isn't it appropriate

01:06:45.290 --> 01:06:47.310
to draw that inference as well?

01:06:47.310 --> 01:06:51.440
&gt;&gt; Eugene Gulland: As I read
the record, beautifully written

01:06:51.440 --> 01:06:59.070
as it is, I'd characterize
Shylock's reaction not

01:06:59.070 --> 01:07:04.510
as surprised, but as
exultant delight.

01:07:04.510 --> 01:07:07.040
[ Laughter ]

01:07:07.040 --> 01:07:09.210
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg: Counselor,
your time is about to run out,

01:07:09.210 --> 01:07:11.260
so if you would like to--

01:07:11.260 --> 01:07:12.670
&gt;&gt; Eugene Gulland: Thank you.

01:07:12.670 --> 01:07:18.010
We, for the reasons argued in
our brief and the arguments

01:07:18.010 --> 01:07:22.060
that I would have made if I not
had so many good questions,--

01:07:22.060 --> 01:07:24.110
[ Laughter ]

01:07:24.110 --> 01:07:30.810
We believe that the
judgment below was correct,

01:07:30.810 --> 01:07:32.580
and that this court should arrive

01:07:32.580 --> 01:07:36.240
at the same judgment
on its own initiative.

01:07:36.240 --> 01:07:37.540
Thank you.

01:07:37.540 --> 01:07:38.840
&gt;&gt; Richard Schneider:
Including conversion.

01:07:38.840 --> 01:07:40.270
&gt;&gt; Eugene Gulland: Absolutely
including conversion.

01:07:40.270 --> 01:07:45.010
That's to save the
eternal soul of Shylock.

01:07:45.010 --> 01:07:47.510
[ Laughter ]

01:07:47.510 --> 01:07:55.040
[ Applause ]

01:07:55.040 --> 01:07:59.390
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg: We will
now hear from Portia's Counsel.

01:08:00.890 --> 01:08:02.190
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns:
Justice Ginsburg,

01:08:02.190 --> 01:08:06.220
and may it please the court,
I am Teresa Miguel-Stearns,

01:08:06.220 --> 01:08:08.440
Counsel for Appellee, Portia.

01:08:08.440 --> 01:08:16.300
Some 400 years ago Portia provided
legal advice to the Duke of Venice

01:08:16.300 --> 01:08:18.680
in a commercial contract dispute

01:08:18.680 --> 01:08:24.070
between Appellant Shylock
and Co-Appellee Antonio.

01:08:24.070 --> 01:08:28.620
This commercial contract
dispute almost turned deadly.

01:08:28.620 --> 01:08:36.480 position:56%
Portia's skillful navigation of
Venetian law saved both men's lives.

01:08:36.480 --> 01:08:42.410
As a direct result in her role
in this Shylock/Antonio dispute,

01:08:42.410 --> 01:08:47.830
Portia has suffered unjustified
targeted attacks to her reputation

01:08:47.830 --> 01:08:51.510
over the course of
the last 400 years.

01:08:51.510 --> 01:08:54.040
[ Laughter ]

01:08:54.040 --> 01:08:58.750
Today, Portia asks that she
be discharged from this case,

01:08:58.750 --> 01:09:02.270
and from any future
related proceedings.

01:09:02.270 --> 01:09:04.530
[ Laughter ]

01:09:04.530 --> 01:09:07.500
Your Honor, we have five
points to our brief.

01:09:07.500 --> 01:09:11.610
However, the heart of our
argument is first and foremost

01:09:11.610 --> 01:09:16.510
that Portia is the wrong
Defendant Appellee in this case.

01:09:16.510 --> 01:09:21.440
And, secondarily, that Portia's
alleged misrepresentations

01:09:21.440 --> 01:09:26.790
to the court, and alleged interest
in the outcome of this matter,

01:09:26.790 --> 01:09:31.090
are without merit, or
at most harmless error.

01:09:31.090 --> 01:09:33.170
[ Laughter ]

01:09:33.170 --> 01:09:35.820
And I will turn to
those matters now.

01:09:35.820 --> 01:09:40.870
First, Portia is the wrong
Defendant Appellee in this case.

01:09:40.870 --> 01:09:44.200
Counsel for Shylock is
well aware that the Duke

01:09:44.200 --> 01:09:48.110
of Venice ruled the city
in the 16th century.

01:09:48.110 --> 01:09:53.380
Portia's role was merely to provide
legal advice to the Duke of Venice,

01:09:53.380 --> 01:09:56.410
who was the ultimate
arbiter in this case.

01:09:56.410 --> 01:10:01.250
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg: But Portia,
although she was not a lawyer,

01:10:01.250 --> 01:10:05.910
we can recognize that she
knew something about the law.

01:10:05.910 --> 01:10:11.410 position:56%
And surely she would have known that
for her, for Portia, to give counsel

01:10:11.410 --> 01:10:18.240
to the Duke, and to Shylock
to stand there unrepresented,

01:10:18.240 --> 01:10:19.540
which he was willing to do

01:10:19.540 --> 01:10:26.730
when he was a Civil Plaintiff
being prosecuted, and no counsel,

01:10:26.730 --> 01:10:30.930
apart from your conflict
of interest being married

01:10:30.930 --> 01:10:39.360
to the principle debtor,
isn't that just overwhelming?

01:10:39.360 --> 01:10:41.250
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns: Your
Honor raises three points.

01:10:41.250 --> 01:10:45.180
And I would like to
address them all.

01:10:45.180 --> 01:10:49.280
First, that Portia was
not learned in the law.

01:10:49.280 --> 01:10:54.100
The record demonstrates that Portia
was indeed learned in the law.

01:10:54.100 --> 01:10:56.650
And in 16th century Venice,

01:10:56.650 --> 01:11:00.560
one did not need a university
diploma, or any time--

01:11:00.560 --> 01:11:01.860
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg:
[inaudible] conceding

01:11:01.860 --> 01:11:03.160
that she was learned in the law.

01:11:03.160 --> 01:11:06.540
Maybe I misspoke or
you misunderstood.

01:11:06.540 --> 01:11:08.090
Portia is learned in the law.

01:11:08.090 --> 01:11:11.510
She had to be to be
such a trickster.

01:11:11.510 --> 01:11:15.340
[ Laughter ]

01:11:15.340 --> 01:11:20.730
But she is displaying her
learning for the benefit

01:11:20.730 --> 01:11:23.710
of Republic of Venice and Antonio.

01:11:23.710 --> 01:11:29.220
And Shylock is standing there
with no one to represent him.

01:11:29.220 --> 01:11:33.130
He is the target of a
criminal prosecution.

01:11:33.130 --> 01:11:37.540
Doesn't he have a right to Counsel?

01:11:37.540 --> 01:11:39.340
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns: Your
Honor, on the issue of notice,

01:11:39.340 --> 01:11:43.180
it was Shylock who dragged
everyone into court.

01:11:43.180 --> 01:11:47.940
Bassanio, the Duke of Venice and
others tried to convince Shylock

01:11:47.940 --> 01:11:50.350
to settle this case amicably

01:11:50.350 --> 01:11:53.340
and financially prior
to coming to court.

01:11:53.340 --> 01:11:55.520
But Shylock craved his bond.

01:11:55.520 --> 01:11:58.020
Shylock wanted his pound of flesh.

01:11:58.020 --> 01:12:02.690
So he brought everyone into
court on a civil proceeding.

01:12:02.690 --> 01:12:06.640
This case never turned
in to a prosecution.

01:12:06.640 --> 01:12:09.310
Portia was never a Prosecutor.

01:12:09.310 --> 01:12:13.190
And the Alien Act remained
a civil forfeiture case.

01:12:13.190 --> 01:12:20.110
As soon as Portia explained to the
Duke of Venice what was involved

01:12:20.110 --> 01:12:25.480
in the Alien Statute, before
Shylock had to utter a word,

01:12:25.480 --> 01:12:30.310
the Duke of Venice immediately
said, "No, we are not going

01:12:30.310 --> 01:12:33.450
to consider this capital
punishment case.

01:12:33.450 --> 01:12:36.250
We will keep it as a
civil forfeiture case."

01:12:36.250 --> 01:12:39.370
And Shylock's estate was
the only thing in jeopardy.

01:12:39.370 --> 01:12:42.330 position:56%
Shylock's life or freedom were never

01:12:42.330 --> 01:12:45.430
in jeopardy throughout the
course of these proceedings.

01:12:45.430 --> 01:12:49.390
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg:
But Shylock never knew

01:12:49.390 --> 01:12:52.320
that the law put him
in that position.

01:12:52.320 --> 01:12:57.050
He said repeatedly,
"I crave the law."

01:12:57.050 --> 01:13:00.990
Had he been counseled, he would
have known what the law was

01:13:00.990 --> 01:13:03.120
and escaped the forfeiture.

01:13:03.120 --> 01:13:04.420
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns:
Respectfully, Your Honor,

01:13:04.420 --> 01:13:07.050
ignorance of the law is no defense.

01:13:07.050 --> 01:13:09.090
[ Laughter ]

01:13:09.090 --> 01:13:10.390
And in this matter--

01:13:10.390 --> 01:13:11.930
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg:
But having no Counsel

01:13:11.930 --> 01:13:14.360
to tell him what the law was.

01:13:14.360 --> 01:13:15.660
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns:
Your Honor, respectfully,

01:13:15.660 --> 01:13:24.810
many people tried to convince
Shylock to settle this case prior

01:13:24.810 --> 01:13:30.180
to it becoming the civil forfeiture
case required by the Alien Act.

01:13:30.180 --> 01:13:37.810
In fact when Portia first
encountered Shylock,

01:13:37.810 --> 01:13:40.930
when she entered the courtroom,
she said, "Who is the Jew

01:13:40.930 --> 01:13:42.360
and who is the merchant?"

01:13:42.360 --> 01:13:46.830
She placed both people, both
participants in this trial,

01:13:46.830 --> 01:13:49.690
at the same level in
the eyes of the law.

01:13:49.690 --> 01:13:50.990
She treated--

01:13:50.990 --> 01:13:52.290
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg:
Who was the Jew,

01:13:52.290 --> 01:13:55.620
not who is the lender
and who is the borrower.

01:13:55.620 --> 01:13:56.920
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns: Right.

01:13:56.920 --> 01:13:58.220
That's correct, Your Honor.

01:13:58.220 --> 01:13:59.520
This is--

01:13:59.520 --> 01:14:00.820
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg: And that--

01:14:00.820 --> 01:14:02.120
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns: This
is what the transcript shows.

01:14:02.120 --> 01:14:03.670
[ Laughter and Applause ]

01:14:03.670 --> 01:14:10.420
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg: We have
another clue to Portia's character.

01:14:10.420 --> 01:14:15.660
So she calls Shylock a Jew.

01:14:15.660 --> 01:14:20.720
Back in Belmont when
Morocco appears, she said,

01:14:20.720 --> 01:14:24.880
"We don't need people of
that dark complexion."

01:14:24.880 --> 01:14:30.280
So we know that this is a woman
who entertains certain biases.

01:14:33.720 --> 01:14:35.460
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns:
Your Honor,

01:14:35.460 --> 01:14:39.990
Portia had a very distinct
idea in Belmont

01:14:39.990 --> 01:14:42.990
that she wanted to marry Bassanio.

01:14:42.990 --> 01:14:45.680
They had laid eyes on
each other in the past.

01:14:45.680 --> 01:14:50.100
And she was hoping that
Bassanio would be the suitor

01:14:50.100 --> 01:14:55.620
who would correctly guess
the box, the casket,

01:14:55.620 --> 01:14:57.300
that her father laid out.

01:14:57.300 --> 01:15:00.250 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Richard Schneider: Was Portia
free to marry anybody she wanted to?

01:15:00.250 --> 01:15:03.060
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns:
No, she was not, Your Honor.

01:15:03.060 --> 01:15:06.760
Portia was a wealthy orphan
whose life was dictated

01:15:06.760 --> 01:15:08.460
by her late father.

01:15:08.460 --> 01:15:13.390
Her late father had
provided for her education,

01:15:13.390 --> 01:15:19.690 position:56%
but had also provided the method for
dictating who her husband would be.

01:15:19.690 --> 01:15:20.990
And--

01:15:20.990 --> 01:15:26.770
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg: That
may have been very patriarchal.

01:15:26.770 --> 01:15:33.600
But she spoke about
Morocco's burnished skin.

01:15:33.600 --> 01:15:40.370
Her love for Bassanio
surely did not require her

01:15:40.370 --> 01:15:45.430 position:56%
to so disparage people from Morocco.

01:15:48.660 --> 01:15:50.510
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns:
That's correct, Your Honor.

01:15:50.510 --> 01:15:53.040
[ Laughter ]

01:15:53.040 --> 01:15:54.340
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg:
So we recognize

01:15:54.340 --> 01:15:57.480
that she has certain
biases based on race

01:15:58.510 --> 01:16:01.890
against Morocco, against Shylock.

01:16:03.010 --> 01:16:04.470
&gt;&gt; Connie Morella: I
would pick up on that.

01:16:04.470 --> 01:16:08.050
I see that clearly as
a conflict of interest.

01:16:08.050 --> 01:16:10.080
[ Inaudible Speaker ]

01:16:10.080 --> 01:16:11.650
&gt;&gt; As a conflict of interest.

01:16:11.650 --> 01:16:15.140
The unclean hand, because
of, you know, Bassanio,

01:16:15.140 --> 01:16:19.990
and she was to gain
from the situation.

01:16:19.990 --> 01:16:21.290
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns: Yes.

01:16:21.290 --> 01:16:23.950
Regarding the conflict of
interest, Portia is alleged

01:16:23.950 --> 01:16:26.930
to have had both a financial
and a personal conflict of--

01:16:26.930 --> 01:16:28.230
&gt;&gt; Connie Morella: Right.

01:16:28.230 --> 01:16:29.530
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns:
Interest in this case.

01:16:29.530 --> 01:16:30.830
I will address both.

01:16:30.830 --> 01:16:32.490
First, the financial
conflict of interest.

01:16:32.490 --> 01:16:36.180
From the very beginning
Portia offered her own ducats

01:16:36.180 --> 01:16:39.180
to settle this case with Shylock.

01:16:39.180 --> 01:16:43.710
Even before she and Bassanio were
married, she offered her ducats

01:16:43.710 --> 01:16:47.660
to Bassanio to help
settle this case amicably.

01:16:47.660 --> 01:16:53.180
When Portia first walked into
court, she pleaded with Shylock

01:16:53.180 --> 01:16:56.390
to settle the case financially.

01:16:56.390 --> 01:17:00.680
Two times the amount, three times
the amount, ten times the amount

01:17:00.680 --> 01:17:03.170
of ducats, of her ducats,

01:17:03.170 --> 01:17:06.280
were offered to Shylock
to settle this case.

01:17:06.280 --> 01:17:07.910
He refused.

01:17:07.910 --> 01:17:11.860
She brought in the Quality of
Mercy speech where she says,

01:17:11.860 --> 01:17:15.680
"The quality of mercy," excuse me,

01:17:15.680 --> 01:17:19.330
"The quality of mercy
is not strained.

01:17:19.330 --> 01:17:23.710
It droppeth as the gentle rain from
heaven upon the place beneath."

01:17:23.710 --> 01:17:25.890
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg:
And where was her mercy?

01:17:25.890 --> 01:17:27.190
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns:
Your Honor,--

01:17:27.190 --> 01:17:28.490
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg:
That's a little bit later.

01:17:28.490 --> 01:17:31.340
She is urging Shylock,
"Be merciful."

01:17:31.340 --> 01:17:36.140
And then she turns on him and
said, "I have no mercy for you."

01:17:36.140 --> 01:17:38.820
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns: I
believe Your Honor is referring

01:17:38.820 --> 01:17:40.120
to the Alien Act.

01:17:40.120 --> 01:17:46.330
And it is actually Portia's mercy
which saves both of their lives.

01:17:46.330 --> 01:17:50.870
Portia is merely providing legal
advice to the Duke of Venice.

01:17:50.870 --> 01:17:58.880 position:56%
When Portia realizes that she is not
able to convince Shylock to amicably

01:17:58.880 --> 01:18:01.310
and financially settle this case,

01:18:01.310 --> 01:18:04.650
she grants him specific
performance on the contract.

01:18:04.650 --> 01:18:07.410
And that is to take
the pound of flesh.

01:18:07.410 --> 01:18:13.050
But at the moment that Shylock is
ready to carve out a pound of flesh

01:18:13.050 --> 01:18:19.080
from Antonio's chest,
Portia stops the proceeding,

01:18:19.080 --> 01:18:24.250
strictly interprets the
contract, which the reference

01:18:24.250 --> 01:18:28.700
that was made earlier, in
that a strict interpretation,

01:18:28.700 --> 01:18:32.700
the contract would require no more,
no less than a pound of flesh,

01:18:32.700 --> 01:18:34.320
and not any other matter.

01:18:34.320 --> 01:18:37.940
No blood, no other
matter, no bone, no organ.

01:18:37.940 --> 01:18:44.820
At that point, she also advises
the Duke that Shylock's actions,

01:18:44.820 --> 01:18:51.800 position:56%
Shylock's attempt to murder Antonio,
which is not in doubt at this point,

01:18:51.800 --> 01:18:54.870 position:56%
is punishable by the Alien Statutes.

01:18:54.870 --> 01:18:56.170
The Alien--

01:18:56.170 --> 01:18:58.910
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg: You're
telling us then that the contract,

01:18:58.910 --> 01:19:02.600
it was impossible to
enforce the contract.

01:19:02.600 --> 01:19:07.960
So the pound of flesh has
to go by impossibility.

01:19:07.960 --> 01:19:12.870
Everyone knows you can't take
flesh without blood as well.

01:19:12.870 --> 01:19:18.100 position:56%
So then what would happen if he
can't get the remedy he's demanding,

01:19:18.100 --> 01:19:20.660
he would get a substitutional
remedy.

01:19:20.660 --> 01:19:24.620
He would get the ordinary
remedy for breach of contract.

01:19:24.620 --> 01:19:28.490 position:56%
That is in this case his money back.

01:19:28.490 --> 01:19:30.760
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns:
Your Honor, respectfully,

01:19:30.760 --> 01:19:34.260
this contract was enforceable
under the laws of Venice.

01:19:34.260 --> 01:19:35.920
This is a commercial contract.

01:19:35.920 --> 01:19:40.880
And Venice, as the international
commercial hegemony that it was,

01:19:40.880 --> 01:19:44.990
required strict enforcement
of all commercial contracts.

01:19:44.990 --> 01:19:46.290
The Duke knew this.

01:19:46.290 --> 01:19:47.590
Antonio knew this.

01:19:47.590 --> 01:19:51.730 position:56%
Antonio even said this to his
friends as he was going into court--

01:19:51.730 --> 01:19:53.030
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg:
But if Portia--

01:19:53.030 --> 01:19:54.330
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns:
That the con--

01:19:54.330 --> 01:19:56.600
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg: Is
correct, the contract is impossible

01:19:56.600 --> 01:20:00.230
to enforce, because you can't
take flesh without taking blood.

01:20:00.230 --> 01:20:02.830
It's an impossibility.

01:20:04.770 --> 01:20:07.070
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns: Your
Honor, it is my understanding

01:20:07.070 --> 01:20:10.510
that with a very hot knife one--

01:20:10.510 --> 01:20:16.040
[ Laughter ]

01:20:16.040 --> 01:20:19.510
One can take flesh without blood.

01:20:19.510 --> 01:20:24.410
[ Laughter ]

01:20:24.410 --> 01:20:30.350
Your Honor, Portia's interest
in this case was to make sure

01:20:30.350 --> 01:20:34.530
that both men walked out
of the courtroom alive,

01:20:34.530 --> 01:20:39.050
not one on a stretcher having his
chest carved out and bled to death,

01:20:39.050 --> 01:20:41.540
and not the other being dragged off

01:20:41.540 --> 01:20:44.960
to the hangman's gallows
to meet his own demise.

01:20:44.960 --> 01:20:50.000
This is the sign of a merciful
judge, not a conflicted one.

01:20:50.000 --> 01:20:51.300
&gt;&gt; Suzanne Reynolds:
Miss Miguel-Stearns,

01:20:51.300 --> 01:20:57.270
I believe it's your position
that Portia did not engage

01:20:57.270 --> 01:20:59.490
in any misrepresentation.

01:20:59.490 --> 01:21:01.100
Is that right?

01:21:01.100 --> 01:21:05.320
You've certainly pointed
to facts in the record

01:21:05.320 --> 01:21:11.080
that do support the conclusion that
she was very learned in the law.

01:21:11.080 --> 01:21:15.360
But didn't she engage
in misrepresentation?

01:21:15.360 --> 01:21:19.340
And, if so, doesn't that
taint the proceeding

01:21:19.340 --> 01:21:22.120
so that the judgment
should be set aside,

01:21:22.120 --> 01:21:24.640
and there should be a retrial?

01:21:24.640 --> 01:21:27.770
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns: Your
Honor, the only misrepresentation

01:21:27.770 --> 01:21:31.800
that Portia made was
disguising herself as a man.

01:21:31.800 --> 01:21:35.830
That she was a woman had
absolutely no bearing

01:21:35.830 --> 01:21:38.240
on the outcome of the case.

01:21:38.240 --> 01:21:41.720
She was legitimately in the
court having been sent there

01:21:41.720 --> 01:21:47.210
by Dr. Bellario to provide legal
advice to the Duke of Venice.

01:21:47.210 --> 01:21:50.440
The Duke of Venice did not
want to enforce the contract,

01:21:50.440 --> 01:21:54.690
even though he felt he needed to,
because the laws of Venice need

01:21:54.690 --> 01:21:58.600
to be strictly enforced in order
to retain it's, as I mentioned,--

01:21:58.600 --> 01:22:00.740
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg:
But did Bellario know

01:22:00.740 --> 01:22:05.150
that Portia was married to the
principle debtor in this case?

01:22:05.150 --> 01:22:06.450
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns:
Your Honor,

01:22:06.450 --> 01:22:08.030
the record is not clear
on that point.

01:22:08.030 --> 01:22:10.050
[ Laughter ]

01:22:10.050 --> 01:22:15.690
However, Dr. Bellario did know
that Portia was learned in the law

01:22:15.690 --> 01:22:19.400
and very capable of providing
appropriate legal advice

01:22:19.400 --> 01:22:20.700
to the Duke.

01:22:20.700 --> 01:22:23.780
Dr. Bellario wrote a letter
personally to the Duke,

01:22:23.780 --> 01:22:28.320
and attested to the Duke that he
and Portia had reviewed the facts

01:22:28.320 --> 01:22:31.590
of the case, had turned
over many books together.

01:22:31.590 --> 01:22:35.030
They had reviewed the
appropriate law in this matter.

01:22:35.030 --> 01:22:38.550
And that Dr. Bellario furnished
Portia with his opinion,

01:22:38.550 --> 01:22:42.470
which on top of Portia's
own legal acumen,

01:22:42.470 --> 01:22:46.330
would provide superb advice
to the Duke of Venice.

01:22:46.330 --> 01:22:50.430
Dr. Bellario knew that she was
going to disguise herself as a man.

01:22:50.430 --> 01:22:53.610
And actually gave her
the robes to do so.

01:22:53.610 --> 01:22:59.470
Dr. Bellario was a trusted legal
adviser of the Duke of Venice,

01:22:59.470 --> 01:23:05.050
and he was ill that day, so
he sent Portia in his stead.

01:23:05.050 --> 01:23:09.790
Portia had no conflict of
interest in this matter,

01:23:09.790 --> 01:23:14.770
other than to see the
dispute resolved amicably,

01:23:14.770 --> 01:23:17.040
and see both men alive.

01:23:17.040 --> 01:23:19.420
&gt;&gt; Connie Morella: Did
she not at some point

01:23:19.420 --> 01:23:24.490
at the end reject Shylock's
request for repayment?

01:23:24.490 --> 01:23:26.000
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns:
Yes, Your Honor, she did.

01:23:26.000 --> 01:23:31.100
And that is because multiple
times throughout the course

01:23:31.100 --> 01:23:33.900
of the proceedings
Shylock had been offered

01:23:33.900 --> 01:23:36.910
to settle the case financially.

01:23:36.910 --> 01:23:44.830
At some point when he finally
said, "No, I demand my bond,"

01:23:44.830 --> 01:23:48.440
and Portia advised that specific
performance would be the only

01:23:48.440 --> 01:23:52.090
remedy, at that point any
negotiations are off the table.

01:23:52.090 --> 01:23:54.520
Venice is a place of no take-backs.

01:23:54.520 --> 01:23:57.560 position:56%
You don't get two chances in Venice.

01:23:57.560 --> 01:24:01.470
Once they passed the point
of settling the case amicably

01:24:01.470 --> 01:24:05.400
and financially, that
door was closed.

01:24:05.400 --> 01:24:09.940
There is no right to say, "Oh,
well, I guess I can't take my pound

01:24:09.940 --> 01:24:12.820
of flesh, so, okay,
let's go back in time.

01:24:12.820 --> 01:24:15.780
I'll take the money and leave."

01:24:15.780 --> 01:24:20.980
That is just not, that is
just not the law in Venice.

01:24:23.140 --> 01:24:26.210
&gt;&gt; Richard Schneider: Portia's
motivation to get involved in this,

01:24:26.210 --> 01:24:29.820
I don't quite understand the
way you're characterizing it.

01:24:29.820 --> 01:24:32.210
She decides to get
involved after she's heard

01:24:32.210 --> 01:24:35.670
that Antonio has lost his ships.

01:24:35.670 --> 01:24:40.790
She says that she decides
that she must help Antonio,

01:24:40.790 --> 01:24:43.570
because Antonio must
be a wonderful person

01:24:43.570 --> 01:24:47.770
since he's the best
friend of her husband.

01:24:47.770 --> 01:24:53.690
And at that point she decides that
she's going to play this trick.

01:24:53.690 --> 01:24:57.790
Doesn't that motivation
in and of itself show

01:24:57.790 --> 01:25:00.630
that she is deeply
conflicted here in terms

01:25:00.630 --> 01:25:07.600
of her interests in the matter?

01:25:07.600 --> 01:25:11.180
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns:
Your Honor, as I've mentioned,

01:25:11.180 --> 01:25:14.770
Portia is not conflicted
in this case.

01:25:14.770 --> 01:25:20.420
It's true that Bassanio
and Antonio were friends.

01:25:20.420 --> 01:25:23.240
But Portia had never met Antonio.

01:25:23.240 --> 01:25:25.090
Portia had never met Shylock.

01:25:25.090 --> 01:25:31.990
Portia was only concerned about
providing proper legal advice,

01:25:31.990 --> 01:25:36.500
and ensuring that both men
walk out of this case alive.

01:25:36.500 --> 01:25:37.800
&gt;&gt; Ruth Bader Ginsburg:
How can you say

01:25:37.800 --> 01:25:39.670
that when the only reason
she went to Bellario,

01:25:39.670 --> 01:25:43.470
and the only reason she
then went to Venice,

01:25:43.470 --> 01:25:49.510
was in the interest of her husband?

01:25:49.510 --> 01:25:50.810
&gt;&gt; Teresa Miguel-Stearns:
Your Honor, Portia,

01:25:50.810 --> 01:25:54.070
as a woman in 16th century Venice,

01:25:54.070 --> 01:25:58.510
had very limited opportunities
to pursue a career.

01:25:58.510 --> 01:26:01.060
[ Laughter ]

01:26:01.060 --> 01:26:06.850
This was an opportunity, not
only to save the life of a friend

01:26:06.850 --> 01:26:13.010
of her husband's, but also to
put her legal education to use.

01:26:13.010 --> 01:26:14.500
[ Laughter ]

01:26:14.500 --> 01:26:16.830
She knew that Dr. Bellario,
her cousin,

01:26:16.830 --> 01:26:19.090
would properly recommend her.

01:26:19.090 --> 01:26:23.830
And Dr. Bellario would not
have recommend a cousin,

01:26:23.830 --> 01:26:28.250
someone who wouldn't be able
to provide legal advice,

01:26:28.250 --> 01:26:32.620
much less a female
cousin, to send into court,

01:26:32.620 --> 01:26:34.990
putting his own reputation
on the line,

01:26:34.990 --> 01:26:38.170
providing advice to
the Duke of Venice.

01:26:38.170 --> 01:26:42.630
Dr. Bellario was a trusted
advisor of the Duke of Venice.

01:26:42.630 --> 01:26:46.420
He was a career member
of the legal community.

01:26:46.420 --> 01:26:52.320 position:56%
And he would not have put his entire
career on the line for Portia.

01:26:52.320 --> 01:26:57.510
Your Honor, I see my time is up.

01:26:57.510 --> 01:27:00.040
[ Laughter ]

01:27:00.040 --> 01:27:05.600
If I may just close by saying
that Portia requests, once again,

01:27:05.600 --> 01:27:08.080
that she be discharged
from this case,

01:27:08.080 --> 01:27:10.800
and relieved of any
liability in this matter.

01:27:10.800 --> 01:27:14.120
Portia did not have a
conflict of interest.

01:27:14.120 --> 01:27:18.530
Her appearance as a man did not
affect the outcome of this case.

01:27:18.530 --> 01:27:21.640
She was qualified to
provide legal advice.

01:27:21.640 --> 01:27:26.530 position:56%
And, but for Portia's legal acumen,
Shylock would have murdered Antonio.

01:27:26.530 --> 01:27:29.590
And Shylock himself
would have been executed.

01:27:29.590 --> 01:27:33.520
Rather, Portia, despite
attempts over and over again

01:27:33.520 --> 01:27:38.140
to convince Shylock to show
mercy, she saved both Shylock's

01:27:38.140 --> 01:27:43.280 position:56%
and Antonio's lives with her
skillful navigation of Venetian law.

01:27:43.280 --> 01:27:47.840
But even if this court does not
agree that Portia acted sincerely,

01:27:47.840 --> 01:27:51.920
Portia is the wrong Defendant
Appellee in this case.

01:27:51.920 --> 01:27:56.340
The Appellee should be the
city state of Venice alone.

01:27:56.340 --> 01:27:58.960
Portia was merciful.

01:28:00.070 --> 01:28:04.160
And in that spirit
would be wholly in favor

01:28:04.160 --> 01:28:08.280
of this court's reversing
the Duke of Venice's order

01:28:08.280 --> 01:28:12.840
that Shylock convert to Judaism.

01:28:12.840 --> 01:28:15.540
Just as Portia would
have liked to of freely

01:28:15.540 --> 01:28:19.500
and openly practiced law
in 16th century Venice.

01:28:19.500 --> 01:28:22.510
And, so, she persisted.

01:28:22.510 --> 01:28:33.160
